What is an Enum?
An enum is a set of named constant values.

ğŸ“Œ In Go â†’ enums are implemented using:
const
custom type
iota

2ï¸âƒ£ Basic Enum Pattern (STANDARD WAY)

type Status int
const (
    Pending Status = iota
    Approved
    Rejected
)

âœ” iota starts from 0
âœ” Increments automatically

3ï¸âƒ£ Why Use Custom Type? (INTERVIEW)
âŒ Bad
const Pending = 0
type Status int
âœ” Type safety
âœ” Better readability
âœ” Compiler checks

4ï¸âƒ£ Enum Values
fmt.Println(Pending)  // 0
fmt.Println(Approved) // 1

5ï¸âƒ£ Enum with Explicit Values
const (
    Low Status = 1
    Medium Status = 5
    High Status = 10
)

6ï¸âƒ£ Enum Starting from 1
const (
    _ Status = iota
    Read
    Write
    Execute
)
ğŸ“Œ _ skips zero value

7ï¸âƒ£ String Enums (VERY IMPORTANT)
Go enums are numbers by default.
For readable output, implement String().

func (s Status) String() string {
    return [...]string{"Pending", "Approved", "Rejected"}[s]
}
fmt.Println(Pending) // Pending

8ï¸âƒ£ Safer String Method (INTERVIEW)
func (s Status) String() string {
    switch s {
    case Pending:
        return "Pending"
    case Approved:
        return "Approved"
    case Rejected:
        return "Rejected"
    default:
        return "Unknown"
    }
}
âœ” Prevents panic

9ï¸âƒ£ Enum Validation (IMPORTANT)
func (s Status) IsValid() bool {
    return s >= Pending && s <= Rejected
}

ğŸ”Ÿ Enum in Switch
switch status {
case Pending:
    fmt.Println("Waiting")
case Approved:
    fmt.Println("Success")
}

1ï¸âƒ£1ï¸âƒ£ Enum with Bit Flags (ADVANCED)
type Permission int

const (
    Read Permission = 1 << iota
    Write
    Execute
)
Usage:
perm := Read | Write

Check:
if perm&Read != 0 {}
ğŸ“Œ Common in OS, permissions.

1ï¸âƒ£2ï¸âƒ£ Enum with String Constants (ALTERNATIVE)
type Status string

const (
    Pending Status = "PENDING"
    Approved Status = "APPROVED"
)
âœ” Human readable
âŒ Less type-safe operations

1ï¸âƒ£3ï¸âƒ£ Enum JSON Marshaling (INTERVIEW)
type Status int

func (s Status) MarshalJSON() ([]byte, error) {
    return json.Marshal(s.String())
}

1ï¸âƒ£4ï¸âƒ£ Zero Value Problem (INTERVIEW TRAP)
var s Status
âœ” s == Pending (zero value)
ğŸ“Œ Always define invalid zero if needed.

1ï¸âƒ£5ï¸âƒ£ Common Interview Traps
âŒ Assuming Go has built-in enum
âŒ Forgetting custom type
âŒ Ignoring zero value
âŒ Unsafe String() indexing

Enum in Go
Go implements enums using const, custom types, and iota.

iota
iota is a counter that resets to zero in each const block.

Why custom type?
To provide type safety and prevent invalid assignments.

ğŸ§  Quick Memory Points
No native enum
Use const + type + iota
Zero value matters
Implement String()
Validate enum values





















































